Race Conditions

Learn about race conditions and how they can affect your application.

We'll cover the following
    • What are race conditions?
    • Using callbacks

What are race conditions?#

Race conditions are uncommon in JavaScript due to its asynchronous nature. But they can be very hard to debug. It is best to handle them before they happen. A race condition is when multiple things happen at once, causing unexpected logic flow. The issue is when Block B executes before Block A, because Block A takes longer to perform.

A basic example is two processes writing on the same file. Without a transactional locking mechanism in place, data is susceptible to corruption. If you expect Process A to finish writing to a file before Process B starts, data could be overwritten, written on top of other data, or any other type of corruption. With transactional locking in place, you ensure Process A is done writing before allowing Process B to write on the same file.

Using callbacks#

The main method to prevent race conditions: make logic transactional in the right place. This is why it is important to both understand and utilize callbacks and promises in JavaScript. Lets take a look at this basic example with and without callbacks from the CSRF generation function we saw in the previous lesson.

Without properly utilized callbacks, you might have something like this:

function generateCsrf(req, res, next) {
    //safe default!
    req.session.csrfToken = null;
    var token = null
    //generate a new token
    var crypto = require('crypto');
    crypto.randomBytes(48, function(err, buffer) {
        //this will run after the below
        //code has been run
        token = buffer.toString('hex');
    });
    //save the token in the session and proceed
    req.session.csrfToken = token;
    //let's try to print the token for this demo
    console.log(token)
    next();
};
Enter to Rename, Shift+Enter to Preview
As you can see our token is still null by time next() has been called.

This would attempt to store the token in req.session.csrfToken and call next() before the token has finished generating. This causes an undefined variable error. Instead, wait until the token generation is complete before you use it.

function generateCsrf(req, res, next) {
    //safe default!
    req.session.csrfToken = null;
    //generate a new token
    var crypto = require('crypto');
    crypto.randomBytes(48, function(err, buffer) {
        var token = buffer.toString('hex');
        //save the token in the session and proceed
        req.session.csrfToken = token;
        //let's try to print the token for this demo
        console.log(token)
        next();
    });
};
Enter to Rename, Shift+Enter to Preview
Our token is set correctly before the function proceeds.

Another example is with database writes. To prevent race conditions in the database, use transactions to apply certain database changes only if all statements are successful.

The general concept: if one thing is supposed to happen at a time, ensure that each step has finished before proceeding to the next step.
